":"Covan","meanings":["English: possibly a variant of   Coven  ."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":9,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Alice Coven was born before 1373, in Waltham, Kent, England, her father, Thomas De Coven, was 38 and her mother, Lora Mordaunt, was 23. She married Nicholas Haute about 1389. They were the parents of at least 4 sons. She died on 11 March 1400, in Kent, Kent, England, and was buried in England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"before 1373–11 March 1400":"enne 1373–11. märts 1400","1373–1400":"1373–1400","1357–1416":"1357–1416","1389–1462":"1389–1462","1390–1462":"1390–1462","1392–1462":"1392–1462","1394–Male":"1394–Surnud","1335–1354":"1335–1354","1350–Female":"1350–Surnud","1462":"146